                    <span>Sam Huntington gave us the phrase "clash of civilizations", which seems to descibe the post-cold war world. Now he has written an intentionally provocative book about the threat to American identity of multiculturalism and multi-lingualism. Even if he overstates his case, what he talks about must be discussed and cannot be swept uder the carpet. </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Thought provoking</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>1</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-02-16</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Aside from any polemic agenda which may be seen in this book Huntington poses thought provoking issues that verbalize what many people often feel.  My reading is that an American "Creed" is not sufficient to hold a national identity.  It may be easy to attack him for saying that.  The "Creed" need to be anchored with more visceral, tangible qualities.  A good accompanying work to this book is John O. King's "The Iron of Melancholy" which outlines the origings of the settler religious psychology.  </span>
                  
